metadata.name: Coronado #140
metadata.description:
This series is about the beauty and charm of imperfection, chaos amidst order, and letting go. It's about knowing that however much control we think we may have, things can all fall apart or burst into something unexpectedly wonderful at any moment, even without our hands tightly on the reigns.

Please see fxtext article linked from main project page for more background on the project and rendering notes.

Some key commands in live mode:

G : Toggle grain
S : Save current resolution
1 : 4000x5000
2 : 6000x7500
3 : 8000x10000
4 : 10000x12500
5 : 12000x15000
6 : 14000x17500
(1-6 work best on Chrome)
(rendering takes longer as resolution increases)

metadata.name: Protein Pelt #212
metadata.description:
An incorrectly placed decimal point led to this pattern. A good friend told me it reminded them of protein structures, I found them to look like animal pelts strewn about.

Each "protein" is made up of 100 pelts, random walking around the canvas from the center. Each "pelt" is made of 5 colors sampled from an array of 84 colors.

Press 's' when in live view to save the image.

metadata.name: Meander River Plot v2 #237
metadata.description: A calmer version of the meander algorithm. Just the loops of the line vectors with no influence from a noise field. I love watching these loop and swirl as I'm developing the piece - it's fun and relaxing.

metadata.name: Fire Card #38
metadata.description:
Fire Cards is a series of generative artworks inspired by 19th-century Japanese fireworks catalogues. The images in these catalogues didn't so much focus on realism, but on the visual associations of the pyrotechnic effects instead. Using a restricted color palette and relatively simple shapes, this resulted in vibrant, graphical posters that sparked your own imagination more than anything else.

In Fire Cards, the abstract, static images are transformed back into lively, dynamic worlds again, each with their own distinctive, centuries-old aesthetics. Using a custom animation and 2D render system, the algorithmically generated worlds slowly build up and show a magical fireworks performance.

Fire Cards are tiny, personal and unique shows of wonder.

metadata.name: Modern Times #108
metadata.description:
Created by Eko33, a generative artist featured at the Tezos Ecosystem Exhibition (Art Basel Miami 2021).

This generative artwork creates a limited series of distinctive artworks based on unique hash seeds.

The algorithmic approach of this collection generates a broad spectrum of unique outcomes, inspired by the "giant machine" from the movie "Modern Times."

Beyond a classic mechanical representation, Eko33 aims to convey multiple emotions while embracing the cold nature of algorithms.

Computer-generated generative art can be seen as a gigantic assembly line. Still, its true nature gives the artist complete freedom from all commercially available tools/constraints.

The collection "Modern Times" highlights the dark ages of generative arts using a bichromatic color palette and evolves toward the contemporary "Digital Renaissance" era using warmer, more acid and "pop" colors.

About Eko33:
Official fx(hash) page: https://www.fxhash.xyz/u/Eko33
Official Website: https://www.eko33.com/

metadata.name: Growth v02 #82
metadata.description:
Growth patterns, version 2. January 2022
Edition of 512

Growth v02 is an generative exploration of patterns in the style of William Morris' iconic wallpaper designs from the 1800s. The code for the Growth series was originally designed to create plausible road networks but has been rewritten to create more organic curved forms. Created with p5js.

'space' to pause the simulation
'h' to toggle to higher res (increases canvas size but runs slower: great for screengrabs)
'r' to reset the seed (some features are locked to the original hash)
's' to save an image to disk
All generated patterns are tile-able horizontally and vertically.

Licensed under CC BY-NC-SA 4.0

This project relies heavily on randomly generated values. It has been thoroughly tested. However, there is always the chance that the wrong combination of randomness can create less-compelling growth. If you feel you version is not living up to the potential promised with this piece, please email me.

metadata.name: Lighthex #13
metadata.description:
Lighthex uses a merge-cell algorithm to determine the base grid shapes with hexagon cells.
Varies in color, cell-count & -size and more. Some features are very rare.

In Live-Mode or when focused...

...click/tap or hit 'SPACE' to play/pause the animation.
...hit 's' or tap with two fingers to save current frame.
...hit 'i' or tap with three fingers to see how the cells are being generated over time.
...use keys 1-5 to save a high-res version of the current frame, the higher the number the higher the resolution.

Or append the following parameters to the url...

...?play=0	-	will stop the animation on the first frame
...?instant=0	-	to see how the cells are being generated over time
...?plot=1	-	will output a B/W lines-only version that can be plotted, hit 'p' to download an SVG-file.


The parameters can be combined using the '&' character, for example:
?plot=1&instant=0


Created with p5.js using map2 and post5.


- @TeNinEightNFTs

metadata.name: The book of tender #18
metadata.description:
The book of tender is a book inspired in kintsugi, an ancient Japanese art technique based on repairing fractures from day-to-day objects, such as ceramics, using golden powder. The philosophy behind this practice, is that fractures and repairs are part of the history of an object. By evidencing them, an object can be perceived in its totality, in its history and transformation.

The book of tender is a book about caring where golden lines encounter the paper texture and in that process it showcases the beauty of healing and the fragility and power of transformation.

Press  from ‚Äú1‚Äù to ‚Äú9‚Äù to render at higher resolutions. If you choose higher resolutions you can follow the animation playing at slower rates.

Press ‚Äús‚Äù to save a .png file at the given resolution.
